\section{Computational Methods}

\subsection{Resonance Structure Enumeration}
The number of resonance structures for a given molecular graph is computed via backtracking with pruning. For a graph with \( m \) bonds, the worst-case complexity is \( O(2^m) \), but typical benzenoids scale as \( O(\theta^{n/2}) \) where \( \theta \) is the golden ratio. For naphthalene (10 carbons, 11 bonds), enumeration takes approximately 0.1 seconds.

\subsection{Spectral Computation}
Eigenvalues and eigenvectors are computed using standard LAPACK routines via NumPy. For graphs with \( n \leq 1000 \), this is practically instant ( < 0.01 seconds ).

\subsection{Homology Computation}
Simplicial homology is computed via boundary matrix reduction over \( \R \). The complexity is \( O(N^3) \) where \( N \) is the number of resonance structures (typically \( N \leq 10^4 \)). For naphthalene with 127 structures, homology computation takes approximately 0.05 seconds.

\subsection{Algorithm Summary}
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Parse SMILES to adjacency matrix and atom list
    \item Enumerate all resonance structures satisfying valence constraints
    \item Build resonance graph using arrow push metric (‖Δ‖₁ = 2)
    \item Compute clique complex
    \item Compute homology groups via boundary matrix reduction
    \item Extract minimal cycle length via BFS
    \item Compute resonance energy: E = 37.5 × L_min
    \item Compute adjacency eigenvalues for HOMO/LUMO
    \item Compute Fukui indices from eigenvectors
    \item Output all properties
\end{enumerate}

